LEGIONELLOSIS - GERMANY (03): (NORTH RHINE-WESTPHALIA), UPDATE
**************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 30 Sep 2014
Source: Das Juelicht [in German, machine trans. edited]
http://www.das-juelicht.de/nachrichten/artikel/14027.php


Searching for possible sources of the legionellosis outbreak in Juelich, another potential source has been identified. The initial samples from the power plant in Weisweiler show high concentrations of _Legionella_ in cooling water, ranging from 7500 colonies in block H to 61 500 colonies [per 100 ml] in block F; the run off from block Q contained 4000 colonies per 100 ml of water. The Weisweiler power plant is located near Juelich in the Aachen region.

Other cooling plants that tested positive for _Legionella_ include the one at the Research Centre in Juelich, as well as the cooling plants at metalworking and plastics processing plants. The cooling towers are now out of service. Whether these findings are causally related to the current outbreak in Juelich is under investigation.

_Legionella_ isolated from the power plant have been sent to a specialized laboratory in Dresden for a comparison with _Legionella_ isolated from patients from Juelich.

The Ministry for the Environment has instructed the district government in Cologne to work together with the owner of the power plant RWE to take measures to reduce the load of _Legionella_. [This probably refers to the Weisweiler power plant owned by RWE (http://www.rwe.com/web/cms/en/60142/rwe-power-ag/locations/lignite/weisweiler-power-plant/). RWE AG (Rheinisch-Westfalisches Elektrizitatswerk AG) is a German electric utilities company based in Essen, North Rhine-Westphalia (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RWE).] In response to the findings, the Ministry has organized a meeting with all involved parties to discuss further measures.

So far, the diagnosis of legionnaires' disease has been confirmed in 30 patients; the latest case dates to 15 Sep 2014.

