[In a prior news report, the legionnaires' disease outbreak in Juelich posted by ProMED-mail (Legionellosis - Germany (02): (NW) update 20140928.2812513), there were 60 cases of suspected legionnaires' disease, of which the diagnosis was confirmed in 23, ruled out in 20, and pending in 17 other cases. There are now 30 confirmed cases. There have been no cases for the past 2 weeks.

The news report likely is referring to genotyping the environmental isolates and comparing the genotypes of environmental isolates with genotypes of clinical isolates. If the clinical isolates have the same genotype, a common source outbreak is likely, and if the genotype of the clinical isolates matches that of an environmental isolate, the facility from which this isolate was obtained is the likely source of the outbreak. We await reports of the results from the Dresden specialty labs' investigation.

Juelich is a town in the district of Dueren, in the federal state of North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JÃ¼lich). North Rhine-Westphalia's capital is Duesseldorf and its biggest city Cologne. 4 of Germany's 10 biggest cities -- Cologne, Duesseldorf, Dortmund, and Essen -- are located in North Rhine-Westphalia. The state is divided into 5 government regions and 31 districts (Kreise) and 23 urban districts (kreisfreie Staedte). A map of the districts can be found at http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/North_Rhine-Westphalia#Subdivisions. - Mod.ML

